This award supported the program of research and development towards the construction of DarkSide-20k, an experiment designed to discover WIMP dark matter or rule out its presence in the allowable space of parameters above the neutrino-induced background (the so-called `neutrino-fog').


The DarkSide-20k experiment is expected to extend the cross-section versus mass range sensitivity in the search for dark matter to 4.610-48 cm2 for a 90% C.L. exclusion and 1.510-47 cm2 at a 5 discovery significance for a 1TeV/c2 WIMP over a 200 tonne-year exposure, well beyond any current or presently funded experiment. The DarkSide-20k search will lead to the discovery, confirmation, or exclusion of the WIMP dark matter hypothesis down to the limit of the `neutrino fog'. DarkSide-20k will also be sensitive to a galactic supernova neutrino burst originating anywhere in the Milky Way Galaxy and to signals from solar neutrinos.


The DarkSide-20k detector is designed to search for dark matter by observing its scatters on target nuclei in 49.7 tonnes of liquefied, ultra-low background argon, with essentially no untagged background from any known physics source beyond coherent neutrino scattering. Any remaining events in the detector then become a potential dark matter discovery.


In order to achieve its science goals, the DarkSide-20k experiment will:

Make use of an argon target extracted from deep underground sources, so that 39Ar is reduced by a factor of 1,000 or higher with respect to argon extracted from the atmosphere;
Exploit of the scintillation light signal for energy measurement and pulse-shape discrimination against backgrounds;
Utilize precise (mm-like) event position reconstruction made possible by the ionization signal;
Rely upon an effective active neutron veto surrounding the dark matter detector;
Benefit from an excellent shielding from background radiation by an active muon veto.



The cutting-edge sensitivity of DarkSide-20k will be enhanced by a combination of proven and demonstrated technologies, including low-radioactivity argon from underground sources, SiPM-based cryogenic photosensors, a ProtoDUNE-like cryostat filled with a 700-tonne buffer of atmospheric argon, and a liquid argon Time Projection Chamber (TPC) constructed from ultra-low background poly(methylmethacrylate) (PMMA, commonly known as acrylic).


The collaborative research project enabled and supported by this award allowed to complete essential R&D tasks, thus enabling the start of the DarkSide-20k construction project.					Last Modified: 12/22/2024

